title: For Trade:  M1A LOADED SAGE EBR
postcontent: Putting this out as a feeler:This rifle started it's life as an M1A Loaded. It appeared to be an older model, because nearly all parts on it were USGI. Rifle was way more accurate than it should have been and after talking to some former CRANE gunsmiths involved in the EBR program, I wanted to see what the rifle was capable of. Added a Sadlak National Match Spring Guide and replaced any remaining commercial internals with USGI ones. Then ordered a SAGE EBR chassis, SAGE EBR Stripper Clip guide, and SAGE Selector Cutout cover for it. Then mounted a set of Badger Ordnance 30MM EBR rings on it. Pretty cool, because they sit low on the gun, yet still allow you to see the iron sights through the cutouts on them. Then decided to make it suppressor ready, and added a Schuster adjustable gas plug, Smith Enterprises GLSH-1 Gas Lock w/ hooded front sight, and a .595"X32 51 tooth Advanced Armament BLACKOUT flash hider / suppressor mount. Also installed a SADLAK Tactical Magazine Release as well as a Smith Enterprises Extended Bolt Stop / Release. Also included with the rifle is a USGI M-14 walnut stock with trap door butt plate, USGI webbed sling, USGI cleaning kit, M1A stock (no cut out, take off of an older model SOCOM 16) and (most, if not all) parts that were replaced. I also have 21 magazines: (1X) unmarked 10 rounder, (2X) Armalite 20 rounders, (7X) CHECK-MATE 20 rounders, and (12X) unmarked 20 rounders. Included as well is a set of USGI castle nut pliers, handguard removal pliers, and a Badger Ordnance bolt grease roller. I also have a Smith Enterprises Gas Lock wrench that I currently can't find, but will include it as soon as it's located.I really love this rifle, but am honestly just get bored with stuff I have and am looking for something new to play with. I don't have a price in mind, but feel free to throw an offer out via PM.Thanks for looking, and feel free to request additional pics, additonal details, questions, or offers via PM.

title: For Sale:  Colt Army National Match 1911A1 45ACP RIA NR! US Military 1968 RIA - Matching - EXC
postcontent: Scarce 1968 Rock Island Arsenal built 1911A1 National Match 45ACP competition pistol. All matching numbers on frame, slide and barrel. Made by the US Military armorers at Rock Island Arsenal this was made in 1968 the last year NM pistols were built. Using a WW2 Remington Rand frame this pistol has all the proper features for a 1968 gun including:Colt NM 7791414 marked slide with matched serial number under the firing pin stopNM 7267718 Barrel BushingAluminum adjustable triggerColt NM 7791414 marked barrel with serial number matching the pistolElliason rear adjustable sight with US stamp on left side (they used this rear sight in 1967, then the Kensight in 1968). Since this pistol bears the SA and RIA stamps its likely RIA rebuilt the gun and left the Ellison in place.Frame has proper milled checkering on front strap along with double T (for targeted) along with NM stamp on right trigger guard. RIA over SA on right side of frame as well indicating this National Match pistol was originally built at Springfield Armory then again by Rock Island…quite common on Army issue National Match Pistols.Only several thousand pistols were made for the matches by military armorers. Using standard WW2 production 1911A1’s, these armorer’s fitted slides, match barrels and other parts allowed as outlined by National Matches. Most of these pistols were rebuilt every few years or so, just like this one. The arsenal finish is excellent showing little wear or marks. Mechanics work well. Bore is mirror bright. Slide to frame fit is super tight.

title: For Sale:  Rare 1941 Llama IV
postcontent: I am listing a hard to find piece of Spanish firearms history, the Llama IV in 9mm or 38, with matching numbers.The gun is in fair condition. It is evident that at one point in time there was some slight surface rust, but the gun has been reblued and is currently rust free. The original grips are missing and have been replaced with some custom (more than likely homemade) target grips. The stampings are light but still visible.The Llama functions well, I test fired it with 50rds of light 38 super loads (well within the firearms original designated chamber pressures) with no apparent failures. The safety is functional, and the gun is a good copy of a 1911, sans grip safety.The model IV was the first gun produced by Llama and were not produced for the American market. The caliber is 9mm largo or 38 acp. The 38 acp is the exact same dimensionally as the 38 super auto, albeit the 38 acp is lower powered than the super. With light 38 super loads, the gun functions marvelously and all internals, including the bore, are in very good shape. It has a 5 1/2” barrel, slightly longer than a standard 1911. Production of the Llama IV started in 1932, with this specific firearm being produced in 1941. If any reference material is needed on this firearm, please email me and I will forward you to where I have found all of my information. I can also send more pictures if needed. These are extremely scarce on the American market, and it is truly a collectible that you will not find anywhere else.Asking price is $700 obo, willing to meet relatively close to Salisbury, NC.
